	<article id="post-902" class="post-902 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-citizenship category-latin-america category-the-sociology-of-citizenship">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902" title="Permalink to Questioning traditional citizenship: memory, identity and collective action in Chile" rel="bookmark">Questioning traditional citizenship: memory, identity and collective action in Chile</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902" title="3:27 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2015-03-13T15:27:06+00:00" pubdate>March 13, 2015</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?author=2" title="View all posts by blogeditor" rel="author">blogeditor</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
						<div class="comments-link">
				<a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Reply</span></a>			</div>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p><em><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sociology-of-citizenship.jpg"><img class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-795" src="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sociology-of-citizenship-150x150.jpg" alt="Sociology of citizenship" width="150" height="150" /></a>By Simón Escoffier</em></p>
<p>In this post I contest traditional liberal conceptions of citizenship rooted in the nation-state and consider the role played by memory in the ways in which Santiago de Chile’s disenfranchised produce contentious politics.</p>
<p>I suggest that, by referring to the past in their meetings and conversations, local neighbourhood organisations in Santiago de Chile’s poor settlements (<em>poblaciones</em>) assert a particular, anti-hegemonic interpretation of history. Through stories, historical anecdotes, and different types of memorials, poor residents produce a neighbourhood identity, giving rise to innovative forms of community membership. <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902#more-902" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&rarr;</span></a></p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
		<footer class="entry-meta">
												<span class="cat-links">
				<span class="entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-cat-links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=95" rel="category">citizenship</a>, <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=77" rel="category">Latin America</a>, <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=98" rel="category">The Sociology of Citizenship</a>			</span>
									
